The sentence "罪魁普京" translates to "Blame Putin" in English. Here, "罪魁" is an idiomatic expression meaning "the principal culprit" or "the chief offender."
MOSCOW – Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden are in agreement: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia’s most prominent opposition figure and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation, which has been critical of President Vladimir Putin.
Fortunately, since Navalny has survived, the relationship between Russia and Germany has not deteriorated further.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Angela Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her eyes, this incident is very serious and can only and must be responded to by the Russian government.
She emphasized that the entire world needs an explanation.
Angela Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this appeal.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government was behind the incident, the EU Commission will impose another round of sanctions.
In any case, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time that Putin's government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and hid.
The Kremlin strongly denies both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitri Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
The director of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, Sergey Naryshkin, even said this was the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, blaming Russia's government for credibility.
Naryshkin's statement clearly amounts to a strained interpretation, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny incident has been more detrimental than beneficial to Russia.
It makes no sense to attempt to poison a prominent political opponent with a Soviet-developed toxin just before a major election.
Especially at this time, when the people in neighboring Belarus are protesting against the August elections, it is even more intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was particularly perplexing.
Shouldn't the Russian government not plan more thoroughly before carrying out the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was really carried out by the Russian government, this assassination would also be a failed operation.
Putin has always been a Darth Vader figure in international politics (the top antagonist from the Star Wars films), interfering in the US election, fomenting street protests in France, encouraging the UK’s Brexit, and backing Syria’s Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, farsighted, and cunning.
Why was he unable to kill Skripal and Navalny though?
Why was Navalny able to flee to Germany and be quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, with the second phase of the Nord Stream natural gas pipeline to Germany facing cancellation.
This murder clearly wasn't worth it.
In fact, this has further fueled public opposition to the Russian authorities' abuses.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies is even more excessive.
If such accusations were true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have mentioned the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely is a conspiracy plotted by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needs Navalny to remain silent before the election, or perhaps it is due to the anti-corruption investigation involving him.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin’s political enforcers,虽 loyal but rather foolish, thought it was a good idea to poison Navalny, and only a few participants knew the truth.
The failed poisonings had similar characteristics in other cases as well: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Public Investigation Committee.
In 2018, there was an attempted poisoning of Peter Verzhelchov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russian judicial abuses.
Further back, it traces to 2006, when Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer, was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Similarly, poisonings of this kind often backfire, just as the Navalny case did.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived; two years later, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death has inflicted significant damage on the image of the Russian government.
This is not to exonerate the Kremlin in any way.
Whether Putin personally commanded or not, the system he created allowed such atrocities to occur. Such a system is both ineffective and useless, merely a farce involving shameless performers.
The death of Navalny is the result that the Kremlin wants, and making Putin, their master, pleased is the ultimate goal of their loyalty.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning attempt fails, they will not be punished.
They did it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find the evidence of poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless of that, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly state that they will take sanctions on Russia, even if it affects their own economies.
Putin created a system centered around Putin.
All responsibilities for what happened in Russia are attributable to him.
